<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06295104 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06295104 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HONG-KONG; REFUGEE; VIETNAM; AGREEMENT; UK  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Vietnam and Britain reached an agreement today to return at least 300Vietnamese boat people to their communist homeland.;   There are 59,000Vietnamese crowded in refugee camps in this British colony, including 19,000who have been denied asylum on the ground they are economic immigrants andcannot prove they are fleeing political persecution.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  VIETNAM, BRITAIN AGREE TO THE RETURN OF 300 BOATPEOPLESTEP IS FIRST IN PLANNED REPATRIATION FROM JAMMEDCAMPS IN HONG KONG  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Today's agreement, announced simultaneously in London and Hong Kong,involves a minimum of 318 boat people who arrived in Hong Kong for a secondtime after voluntarily returning earlier to Vietnam, Hong Kong officialssaid.;   A government statement said the repatriation of the &quot;double-backers&quot;was the first step in talks among Britain, Hong Kong and Vietnam to implementa plan to return home all Vietnamese classified as economic immigrants.;   Itsaid no date has been set for the return of the 318 refugees but that theirrepatriation would not occur for several weeks.;   Talks among the threeparties on the other boat people continued today in Hanoi, the capital ofVietnam, said a Foreign Office spokesman in London.;   The spokesman, who wasnot named in keeping with government policy, refused to say whether forcewould be used to return the 318 Vietnamese but that repatriation would be &quot;inaccordance with normal international procedures.&quot;;   Hong Kong's statementsaid Vietnamese officials promised that &quot;no illegal immigrant who returns toVietnam will face persecution.&quot;;   The United States opposes any forced returnof Vietnamese to their communist homeland.;   Since 1988, the Hong Konggovernment has granted refugee status -- and thus the chance of resettlementin the West -- only to those Vietnamese who prove they fled persecution fromauthorities in Vietnam.;   In 1989, Hong Kong forcibly repatriated 51 boatpeople to Vietnam, triggering an international outcry that forced it toabandon the policy.;   Today's announcement followed talks last month amongBritish, Hong Kong and Vietnamese officials on the boat people issue.;   Sincereports of an agreement between Britain and Vietnam on the boat peoplesurfaced two weeks ago, Vietnamese in Hong Kong, which is to revert to Chineserule in 1997, have staged protests almost daily.;   There were no reports oftrouble today in the camps.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Hong Kong  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911021  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  355  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, October 21, 199100295104,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>